article.description: Jason Kidd had 17 points, 11 assists and seven rebounds and single-handedly halted New York's rally from a 29-point deficit in leading the Nets to a 115-93 victory over the Knicks on Friday night.
article.headline: Nets win fifth straight over Knicks with ease

images.name: Knick fans 020222 inline
images.caption: Beleaguered Knicks fans long for the good, old days when Jeff Van Gundy squeezed out wins.

article.linkText: Kidd thwarts Knicks' comeback; Nets win fifth straight over New York
article.story:
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- The New Jersey Nets don't have a rivalry with the New York Knicks anymore. Instead, it's a mismatch. Jason Kidd had 17 points, 11 assists and seven rebounds and single-handedly halted New York's rally from a 29-point deficit in leading the Nets to a 115-93 victory over the Knicks on Friday night. "We're just a better ball team, basically," second-year forward Kenyon Martin said after the Nets posted their third lopsided win over the Knicks this season. "They've been the team in this area for so long," Martin added. "We go out with extra emphasis on these games. Everybody always downplayed what we've been doing. We want everybody to realize we're the better team in this area." A glance at the standings will confirm that. The first Nets (37-17) not only hold a 16½-game lead over the last-place Knicks (20-33) in the Atlantic Division, they also have the best record in the Eastern Conference. "We understand the tradition and the reputation that the Knicks have," said Kidd, who has transformed the Nets from a laughingstock into a title contender in less than a year. "They were so dominant for years. We want to fill those shoes." Rookie Richard Jefferson had a career-high 22 points and Kerry Kittles had 20 as the Nets had six players in double figures in winning their fifth straight game and sending the Knicks to their fourth straight loss. It also gave New Jersey a five-game winning streak over New York, the first time that's happened since an 11-game run from 1983-86. "They're a better basketball team right now, that's what it boils down to," Knicks point guard Mark Jackson said. "They're a better basketball team. It's as simple as that." Latrell Sprewell was the only Knick who showed any desire in the team's first game since the trading deadline came and went without New York making a deal. Sprewell had 21 of his 30 points in the second quarter in leading the Knicks back from a 51-22 deficit. His performance cut the lead to 13 at the half, and New York got it down to 65-59 in the opening minutes of the third quarter when Sprewell hit a 3-pointer and Othella Harrington followed with two baskets. That's when Kidd took over. He scored seven straight points, including a great layup on a crossover dribble, and assisted on three baskets by Kittles in a 19-6 burst that gave New Jersey an 84-65 lead with 5:08 to play. With Sprewell cooling off and Allan Houston practically invisible after a 34-point effort against Chicago on Wednesday, the Knicks never threatened again. Houston finished with six points on 2-of-9 shooting. Long regarded as one of the NBA's better defensive teams, the Knicks played little defense in the first half. New Jersey moved the ball inside with ease and hit open jumper after open jumper in making 22 of their first 31 shots. "One of the advantages they have as a team is they create mismatches," Knicks coach Don Chaney said. "It's hard to guard them." The Nets, who never trailed, ballooned a 34-20 first-quarter lead to 51-22 with a 17-2 spurt to open the second quarter. Lucious Harris had seven points in the run and Jefferson hit consecutive 3-pointers.

Game notes
The sellout of crowd of 20,049 was the Nets' third of the season ... Nets center Todd MacCulloch was placed on the injured list with an inflammation of the left foot ... This marks the first time in franchise history that the Nets (37-17) have been 20 games over .500. ... New York is 6-19 on the road this season. New Jersey is 22-6 at the Continental Airlines Arena. ... The Nets other wins over the Knicks were by scores of 109-83 and 114-96. ... Clarence Weatherspoon was supposed to start for New York but he didn't because of a sprained ankle. He had six points in 19 minutes off the bench.
